00:48:37,920 --> 00:48:38,920
I shot him.

705
00:48:38,920 --> 00:48:44,160
And we just all laughed at my uncle.

706
00:48:44,160 --> 00:48:46,520
And she said, you know, that's crazy.

707
00:48:46,520 --> 00:48:48,520
You want me to fix it.

708
00:48:48,520 --> 00:48:50,760
So there's nothing I can do with your TV.

709
00:48:50,760 --> 00:48:53,440
And he turned and walked away.

710
00:48:53,440 --> 00:48:56,600
And you can see my uncle had good sense with this man.

711
00:48:56,600 --> 00:49:01,360
They were looking at a lot of white people who were like inferior to them in a way.

712
00:49:01,360 --> 00:49:03,600
That's the way they looked at them.

713
00:49:03,600 --> 00:49:11,240
And they didn't allow anyone to beat up on them, a mystery thing, even when they worked

714
00:49:11,240 --> 00:49:13,440
for whites.

715
00:49:13,440 --> 00:49:18,600
They used to tell us these stories about how they got in a fight with this person.

716
00:49:18,600 --> 00:49:19,920
We beat him up or whatever.

717
00:49:19,920 --> 00:49:20,920
And they were white.

718
00:49:20,920 --> 00:49:24,320
And I just sit there mumbling, oh, that's fantastic.

719
00:49:24,320 --> 00:49:30,560
You know, because it was just the opposite image that you had of the downtrodden negro.

720
00:49:30,560 --> 00:49:32,440
They just weren't like that.

721
00:49:32,440 --> 00:49:35,080
And so that was the model we got.

722
00:49:35,080 --> 00:49:42,840
And we felt that when we joined the movement, we were doing what they prepared us to do.

723
00:49:42,840 --> 00:49:44,840
And they were all very proud of it.

724
00:49:44,840 --> 00:49:54,240
They were all unique because in that just, it was the prevailing culture.

725
00:49:54,240 --> 00:50:01,240
And I think it's about the shift of teenagers into movement activity.

726
00:50:01,240 --> 00:50:09,240
And especially after 1960, before we started today, Dr. Lamy were talking about just that

727
00:50:09,240 --> 00:50:14,240
rush feeling, so much excitement and whole Oscar events.

728
00:50:14,240 --> 00:50:18,240
I'm already quite surprised to talk about that.

729
00:50:18,240 --> 00:50:23,240
The movement was the most exciting thing that one could engage in.

730
00:50:23,240 --> 00:50:27,520
I often say that, in fact, I coined the term the Emmett Till generation.

731
00:50:27,520 --> 00:50:36,000
I say that there was no more exciting time to have been born at the time and the place

732
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:40,920
and to the parents that movement, young movement people were born to.

733
00:50:40,920 --> 00:50:48,480
It was through an accident of history that we were at post-war generation in the South.

734
00:50:48,480 --> 00:50:54,240
At the time, we had the parents who taught us stand up for yourself.

735
00:50:54,240 --> 00:51:00,880
That all of that thing, I mean, you're talking about synchronicity and serendipity.

736
00:51:00,880 --> 00:51:07,400
All those things fell into place for a small group of young people.

737
00:51:07,400 --> 00:51:10,760
And that was our generation.

738
00:51:10,760 --> 00:51:12,880
We were post-war kids.

739
00:51:12,880 --> 00:51:16,600
Some of our parents had gone, fathers had gone abroad to fight for freedom that came

740
00:51:16,600 --> 00:51:18,920
back and they were so disappointed.

741
00:51:18,920 --> 00:51:24,720
We were that of the era, they had been in the North as suburbanization of America, you

742
00:51:24,720 --> 00:51:34,520
know, where the white kids, fathers were getting the jobs and they had the economics to expansion

743
00:51:34,520 --> 00:51:36,360
and the material goods.

744
00:51:36,360 --> 00:51:38,560
And we saw that we weren't getting those.

745
00:51:38,560 --> 00:51:44,640
We were that generation that had been brought up with a fire and brimstone of believing

746
00:51:44,640 --> 00:51:50,920
that they were old testament prophets on justice and, you know, just a strong sense of right

747
00:51:50,920 --> 00:51:51,920
and wrong.

748
00:51:51,920 --> 00:51:55,360
It was the morality of our times.

749
00:51:55,360 --> 00:52:03,660
We believed that it was, according to the Bible, it was wrong to segregate people and

750
00:52:03,660 --> 00:52:07,840
to treat one group of people better than the other.

751
00:52:07,840 --> 00:52:13,320
We grew up with the liturgy of the Baptist Church that we translated to the Civil Rights

752
00:52:13,320 --> 00:52:21,760
Movement with the songs and the preaching and the testifying all that took place in those

753
00:52:21,760 --> 00:52:23,520
mass meetings.

754
00:52:23,520 --> 00:52:28,360
All of these were factors and we were, of that generation where most important of all

755
00:52:28,360 --> 00:52:38,000
was that all of us were imbued with the sense by our parents and aunts and uncles and

756
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:44,960
our neighbors who said that you are the generation that will do better and your generation will

757
00:52:44,960 --> 00:52:45,960
change things.

758
00:52:45,960 --> 00:52:52,840
I remember so clearly Uncle Archive who was in World War I went to France and he always

759
00:52:52,840 --> 00:52:56,360
told us your generation is going to change things.

760
00:52:56,360 --> 00:53:02,520
And so there was these expectations of us and I think we fulfilled them but I don't believe

761
00:53:02,520 --> 00:53:03,520
those.

762
00:53:03,520 --> 00:53:14,360
It was through, obviously it was not a matter of a king standing up in Montgomery and people

763
00:53:14,360 --> 00:53:22,000
saying well you're right, it was, for us it was almost like you had to do it.

764
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:23,080
It was a matter of time.

765
00:53:23,080 --> 00:53:27,200
The time had come and they expected so much of us.

766
00:53:27,200 --> 00:53:28,480
Our teachers used to tell us.

767
00:53:28,480 --> 00:53:32,760
These were the first, sometimes the first generation to go to college too.

768
00:53:32,760 --> 00:53:34,560
That was critical.

769
00:53:34,560 --> 00:53:40,120
They said they got a good education because no one can take that from you and I think

770
00:53:40,120 --> 00:53:43,600
often my mother used to say that all the time.

771
00:53:43,600 --> 00:53:47,000
But she grew up with her time when people took their labor from them.

772
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:51,600
They took everything from them and gave them little compensation for anything.

773
00:53:51,600 --> 00:53:58,280
Our stepfather made $30 or $35 a week as a skilled mechanic, diesel engine mechanic.

774
00:53:58,280 --> 00:54:02,800
His employee used to send him to New Orleans to his training courses.

775
00:54:02,800 --> 00:54:10,800
And he retired on Social Security whereas the white men working alongside him had pensions.

776
00:54:10,800 --> 00:54:16,040
They understood the injustices and while they may have felt they couldn't do anything about

777
00:54:16,040 --> 00:54:17,040
they.

778
00:54:17,040 --> 00:54:22,120
There was this spirit of rising expectations that we would do it.

779
00:54:22,120 --> 00:54:23,320
We had so many mentors.

780
00:54:23,320 --> 00:54:27,680
I remember one of our mentors was an herbalist.

781
00:54:27,680 --> 00:54:35,200
We called him Dr. McLeod and he called him Cuz he was a cousin of our aunt.

782
00:54:35,200 --> 00:54:38,040
He used to come and sit on the porch and talk to mother.

783
00:54:38,040 --> 00:54:41,360
He was a member of the local Hesseburg branch in WCT.

784
00:54:41,360 --> 00:54:47,240
He subscribed to the Pittsburgh Courier and Chicago defender, Jet and Ebene magazine.

785
00:54:47,240 --> 00:54:50,040
He read so he would bring us books.

786
00:54:50,040 --> 00:54:52,280
He brought us every week.

787
00:54:52,280 --> 00:54:54,640
He brought us these publications.

788
00:54:54,640 --> 00:54:58,800
And that was on the outside reading material that we got.

789
00:54:58,800 --> 00:55:00,800
Because everything was censored.

790
00:55:00,800 --> 00:55:01,800
Everything.

791
00:55:01,800 --> 00:55:02,800
The radio.

792
00:55:02,800 --> 00:55:06,160
There was one TV station in Hesseburg.

793
00:55:06,160 --> 00:55:07,960
I remember when it came.

794
00:55:07,960 --> 00:55:12,840
Arraped and they would call you Niggas on screen.

795
00:55:12,840 --> 00:55:19,920
And we, that outside information just fueled our curiosity and fated and made us

796
00:55:20,920 --> 00:55:23,840
want to see the world and do things differently.

797
00:55:23,840 --> 00:55:27,120
It gave us the window into how the outside lived.

798
00:55:27,120 --> 00:55:33,640
I mean, we saw that kids were going to college in Chicago and in Pittsburgh and all over

799
00:55:33,640 --> 00:55:34,840
the North.

800
00:55:34,840 --> 00:55:40,040
And it allowed us to see how other people were actually living.

801
00:55:40,040 --> 00:55:42,520
And that could be ours as well.

802
00:55:42,520 --> 00:55:45,640
But first we had to get rid of this little mat of segregation.

803
00:55:45,640 --> 00:55:46,640
Discrimination.

804
00:55:46,640 --> 00:55:53,640
Your first semester, or first year at the Jackson State would be a very busy one.

805
00:55:53,640 --> 00:55:54,640
Yes.

806
00:55:54,640 --> 00:55:58,640
No, it was a direction in terms of your culture.

807
00:55:58,640 --> 00:55:59,640
Right.

808
00:55:59,640 --> 00:56:00,640
See, we met Mega.

809
00:56:00,640 --> 00:56:03,880
Well, I'll talk about that.

810
00:56:03,880 --> 00:56:10,400
We met Mega Evans in high school when he came to Hesseburg to set up a, a, and in

811
00:56:10,400 --> 00:56:12,040
WCV youth chapter.

812
00:56:12,040 --> 00:56:18,040
He came down, but Clack and Arden, Vernon Damer, were the two people behind really.

813
00:56:18,040 --> 00:56:23,040
The old Hesseburg, and WCV chapter did, but those two were the motivating factors behind

814
00:56:23,040 --> 00:56:24,040
our chapter.

815
00:56:24,040 --> 00:56:29,040
And the pianist, Vernon Damer's sister, played a piano in our church.

816
00:56:29,040 --> 00:56:31,040
Her name was Hallean Beer.

817
00:56:31,040 --> 00:56:32,040
She was my best friend.

818
00:56:32,040 --> 00:56:39,520
She would, mother would let us go to NWCP meetings in Jackson with her and Mr. Damer.

819
00:56:39,520 --> 00:56:42,000
And since she was in the church, there was nothing.

820
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:43,000
The mother trusted her.

821
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:48,000
You know, so, and our ears were wide open and taking it all in.

822
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:51,000
Clack and Arden, they drove up to Jackson and they took us with them.

823
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:54,000
And Clack and Arden, you're also interested in Negro rights.

824
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:55,000
So we called it.

825
00:56:55,000 --> 00:57:00,000
Clack and Arden was our youth chapter advisor.

826
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:08,840
And, but the tragic thing was that we were so young when he was jailed and we knew that

827
00:57:08,840 --> 00:57:09,840
it wasn't right.

828
00:57:09,840 --> 00:57:14,040
The first time he went on campus and they said, they found moonshine in his car.

829
00:57:14,040 --> 00:57:17,160
We were looking at it from a distance.

830
00:57:17,160 --> 00:57:18,560
We knew him.

831
00:57:18,560 --> 00:57:25,280
We didn't think that he would ever do anything like that, but it was so far away from him.

832
00:57:25,280 --> 00:57:29,680
And when he was incarcerated, he stayed in jail in Hesseburg over a year.

833
00:57:29,680 --> 00:57:31,840
And we could go downtown and walk past the jail.

834
00:57:31,840 --> 00:57:32,840
And you wouldn't go up there.

835
00:57:32,840 --> 00:57:36,160
But you didn't dare try to even go.

836
00:57:36,160 --> 00:57:38,160
And we didn't even know how to negotiate going in.

837
00:57:38,160 --> 00:57:41,160
No, there was no movement of any sort.

838
00:57:41,160 --> 00:57:44,160
It was all too feel to into.

839
00:57:44,160 --> 00:57:47,160
But later learned there was an underground movement.

840
00:57:47,160 --> 00:57:48,160
But these were all adults.

841
00:57:48,160 --> 00:57:49,160
We were kids.

842
00:57:49,160 --> 00:57:54,560
The other thing you have to think about here is that look at this from the perspective of

843
00:57:54,560 --> 00:58:04,160
14, 15-year-olds who know these things are not right and who would just love to someday

844
00:58:04,160 --> 00:58:09,280
figure out how to make everything right.

845
00:58:09,280 --> 00:58:15,440
But being also being very powerless, I will never forget how during our respond to Emmett

846
00:58:15,440 --> 00:58:17,480
Till's lynching.

847
00:58:17,480 --> 00:58:24,960
We used to go to the Hudson store every day at 4, 15, 4, 15, 4, 20.

848
00:58:24,960 --> 00:58:32,480
That was when we had the city bus ran, went through to from downtown Hesseburg out to

849
00:58:32,480 --> 00:58:34,840
Palmest Crossing.

850
00:58:34,840 --> 00:58:39,280
And they brought the Hesseburg American on that bus at 4, 15, 4, 20.

851
00:58:39,280 --> 00:58:43,680
And we ran up there with the damn every day and bought out a copy of the newspaper.

852
00:58:43,680 --> 00:58:51,480
And I remember I used to clip out, clip the paper about Emmett Till's lynching and talk

853
00:58:51,480 --> 00:58:58,920
about feeling powerless and frightened but also just like this is awful.

854
00:58:58,920 --> 00:59:04,840
But that was my realization that if these men are guilty, why aren't they being punished?

855
00:59:04,840 --> 00:59:05,840
Right.

856
00:59:05,840 --> 00:59:06,840
And Dora wanted to be a lawyer then.

857
00:59:06,840 --> 00:59:08,600
That's what a light bulb went off.

858
00:59:08,600 --> 00:59:10,600
Why aren't they being punished?

859
00:59:10,600 --> 00:59:18,680
And that's when I went on my quest to try and understand the whole legal system and equal

860
00:59:18,680 --> 00:59:20,680
rights and justice under the law.

861
00:59:20,680 --> 00:59:28,840
Dora used to have, let me finish, to talk about the Constitution.

862
00:59:28,840 --> 00:59:35,040
And I went to my social studies teacher, Mr. Clark, and asked him, what does it, 13, 14,

863
00:59:35,040 --> 00:59:36,040
15 amendments mean?

864
00:59:36,040 --> 00:59:39,080
He said, this is something to do with the Constitution.

865
00:59:39,080 --> 00:59:44,320
I went and found a copy of the Constitution and memorized these articles.

866
00:59:44,320 --> 00:59:47,480
The America's Creed, the pre-eminent to the Constitution, all of this.

867
00:59:47,480 --> 00:59:49,280
I'm sorry to repeat these all the time.

868
00:59:49,280 --> 00:59:51,960
From my own empowerment.

869
00:59:51,960 --> 00:59:59,600
And that was something that I felt that I could do for myself and maybe rule it off on

870
00:59:59,600 --> 01:00:00,600
somebody else.

871
01:00:00,600 --> 01:00:03,160
But that's how powerless I felt.

872
01:00:03,160 --> 01:00:05,640
And these men are guilty.

873
01:00:05,640 --> 01:00:08,120
And I hope they don't come down here and get me.

874
01:00:08,120 --> 01:00:10,800
And I hope anybody else.

875
01:00:10,800 --> 01:00:14,160
And it was Mississippi, was the closed society.

876
01:00:14,160 --> 01:00:16,160
But it's a vulnerability.

877
01:00:16,160 --> 01:00:17,160
It's a vulnerability.

878
01:00:17,160 --> 01:00:19,680
I think cannot be overemphasized.

879
01:00:19,680 --> 01:00:25,520
And we had two colleges there, Cary College and Southern.

880
01:00:25,520 --> 01:00:32,800
And Southern was so racist, and what Clark can all try to enroll, they built a special

881
01:00:32,800 --> 01:00:34,640
dorm for the students from Latin America.

882
01:00:34,640 --> 01:00:36,880
And they had a lot of South American students too.

883
01:00:36,880 --> 01:00:39,640
They stayed in a separate dorm.

884
01:00:39,640 --> 01:00:41,400
They built it for them.

885
01:00:41,400 --> 01:00:47,200
They built one recently for the Native Americans to live in on the same college.

886
01:00:47,200 --> 01:00:48,200
Right now, yes.

887
01:00:48,200 --> 01:00:49,600
I'm not going to speak.

888
01:00:49,600 --> 01:00:55,080
So when we would go downtown, we would hear them speaking in this foreign tongue, but

889
01:00:55,080 --> 01:00:57,200
we didn't understand what they were saying.

890
01:00:57,200 --> 01:01:02,400
But it was a very curious kind of thing because we didn't see anybody but the people around

891
01:01:02,400 --> 01:01:03,400
us.

892
01:01:03,400 --> 01:01:07,080
And when we, Joe, and I would hear this, and we want to know who are these people, where

893
01:01:07,080 --> 01:01:09,360
they come from, what are they saying?

894
01:01:09,360 --> 01:01:10,720
And was just wanting to know more.

895
01:01:10,720 --> 01:01:11,720
It's curious.

896
01:01:11,720 --> 01:01:13,440
It just wanted to know more.

897
01:01:13,440 --> 01:01:15,120
Wanted to know what was beyond.

898
01:01:15,120 --> 01:01:19,720
We would go to New Orleans, occasionally, to the Gulf Coast, but not therefore out of

899
01:01:19,720 --> 01:01:24,120
that little circle, the church, school, and home, and family.

900
01:01:24,120 --> 01:01:25,680
And with friends.

901
01:01:25,680 --> 01:01:26,680
But we also...

902
01:01:26,680 --> 01:01:27,680
Sure, sure.

903
01:01:27,680 --> 01:01:36,520
I just want to say, we would take the case of Clacknown as one that's perfectly illustrated

904
01:01:36,520 --> 01:01:41,960
the way the White Authority would chop up some charge just to take someone out of the

905
01:01:41,960 --> 01:01:46,200
landscape where he's going to work with Black Youth and so on.

906
01:01:46,200 --> 01:01:47,200
Right.

907
01:01:47,200 --> 01:01:48,200
Right.

908
01:01:48,200 --> 01:01:51,960
And we did not know anything about his background.

909
01:01:51,960 --> 01:01:56,520
And the University of Chicago was far into us.

910
01:01:56,520 --> 01:01:58,280
We did know he was, in quote, smart.

911
01:01:58,280 --> 01:01:59,280
Yeah.

912
01:01:59,280 --> 01:02:00,280
We knew he was smart.

913
01:02:00,280 --> 01:02:05,000
But later on we found out he was touring one of the Jewish kids there in Hattiesburg,

914
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:08,960
who was found on the big store, the department store.

915
01:02:08,960 --> 01:02:15,720
And so, but he was very kind and very quiet, he's going.

916
01:02:15,720 --> 01:02:17,240
And Medgev was the same way.

917
01:02:17,240 --> 01:02:21,880
Now, we were teenagers and they took the tent with us.

918
01:02:21,880 --> 01:02:22,880
We were young with us.

919
01:02:22,880 --> 01:02:28,960
And this is the one thing about SNCC that I still marvel over and still think about.

920
01:02:28,960 --> 01:02:32,760
At my age, would I follow a 19-year-old kid somewhere?

921
01:02:32,760 --> 01:02:33,760
Right.

922
01:02:33,760 --> 01:02:38,760
And that was the way we were presenting ourselves to the...

923
01:02:39,080 --> 01:02:41,000
People in the community, the community organization.

924
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:45,040
And I think the reason a lot of these people took us seriously, most of them took us seriously,

925
01:02:45,040 --> 01:02:47,120
was because we took ourselves seriously.

926
01:02:47,120 --> 01:02:50,200
And because we weren't asking them to do something that we weren't already doing.

927
01:02:50,200 --> 01:02:52,600
Well, we had a message also that was a message.

928
01:02:52,600 --> 01:02:53,600
They resonated with that.

929
01:02:53,600 --> 01:02:55,720
A message that they had been waiting to hear.

930
01:02:55,720 --> 01:02:56,720
Right.

931
01:02:56,720 --> 01:03:01,760
And the Christian bothers in a little child should lead them.

932
01:03:01,760 --> 01:03:04,920
And I think that that was part of the whole thing too.

933
01:03:04,920 --> 01:03:11,440
But looking back at it and thinking they had lived hard lives.

934
01:03:11,440 --> 01:03:12,680
It worked very hard.

935
01:03:12,680 --> 01:03:13,680
Right.

936
01:03:13,680 --> 01:03:23,040
And to get people to leave their jobs, waitress in a cafe, house in the tent,

937
01:03:23,040 --> 01:03:29,120
maize and sharecroppers, to go to the courthouse in Indian oil and Mississippi where Miss Fannie

938
01:03:29,120 --> 01:03:30,120
Lou Hamer went.

939
01:03:30,520 --> 01:03:37,880
In August of 1962, to get a busload of people to go and risk their lives and their jobs

940
01:03:37,880 --> 01:03:41,720
and everything else to go there and stay all day long.

941
01:03:43,720 --> 01:03:46,280
It's something that I marvel at right now.

942
01:03:46,280 --> 01:03:48,680
Wondering how did it happen?

943
01:03:48,680 --> 01:03:51,080
Where did they get that?

944
01:03:51,080 --> 01:03:52,720
But they were ready for it.

945
01:03:52,720 --> 01:03:54,240
The time was right.

946
01:03:54,240 --> 01:03:55,080
The time was right.

947
01:03:55,080 --> 01:03:56,400
This is 1962.

948
01:03:56,400 --> 01:03:59,520
So we talk about Miss Rosa Parks.

949
01:03:59,520 --> 01:04:07,360
And while we were sitting here talking, Emmett Till's death resonated because it was so publicized.

950
01:04:07,360 --> 01:04:10,080
I heard a little about Miss Rosa Parks.

951
01:04:10,080 --> 01:04:12,680
But there was not much information.

952
01:04:12,680 --> 01:04:17,440
All we knew was that Black people were not riding the buses.

953
01:04:17,440 --> 01:04:18,920
And that was about it.

954
01:04:18,920 --> 01:04:25,360
But when Emmett Till's picture was shown, that was what blew the iconic photograph.

955
01:04:25,360 --> 01:04:29,880
That was the image for our generation to galvanize our generation.

956
01:04:29,880 --> 01:04:30,880
And all of us saw it.

957
01:04:30,880 --> 01:04:32,720
We saw it on the cover of Jet Magazine.

958
01:04:32,720 --> 01:04:37,480
And recently, I was watching, two weeks ago, I was watching TV one.

959
01:04:37,480 --> 01:04:45,960
And they had this documentary on, I can't call this name right now, but on Emmett Till.

960
01:04:45,960 --> 01:04:54,200
And Mrs. Mowley was talking, Emmett Till's mother was talking.

961
01:04:54,200 --> 01:04:58,280
And she was describing how he looked when she went to the funeral.

962
01:04:58,280 --> 01:05:02,080
They wanted to bury him right then and there without opening the casket.

963
01:05:02,080 --> 01:05:05,280
And she went on, she said, no, I don't have time to faint.

964
01:05:05,280 --> 01:05:07,960
I don't have time to do this, crying all this.

965
01:05:07,960 --> 01:05:11,240
So she described each part of his body.

966
01:05:11,240 --> 01:05:17,000
And all of a sudden, I told my daughter, I'm going to sleep.

967
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:18,200
And this was three weeks ago.

968
01:05:18,200 --> 01:05:22,880
I could not at this age let that into my psyche.

969
01:05:22,880 --> 01:05:26,920
I just went straight to sleep and slept maybe two hours.

970
01:05:26,920 --> 01:05:28,360
And then I woke up.

971
01:05:28,360 --> 01:05:33,120
I just thought everyone I knew and said, can not see it.

972
01:05:33,120 --> 01:05:35,320
Everyone I knew and snickered.

973
01:05:35,320 --> 01:05:38,480
Every black sub in a fashure had seen that photograph.

974
01:05:38,480 --> 01:05:42,240
And it was like the clarion call for action.

975
01:05:42,240 --> 01:05:47,640
And that when we got older, we were going to avenge his death.

976
01:05:47,640 --> 01:05:49,600
I mean, I can remember feeling that so strongly.

977
01:05:49,600 --> 01:05:52,480
I remember clipping those Hattiesburg Americans.

978
01:05:52,480 --> 01:05:56,240
Each time there was an article about Emmett Till case in the trial.

979
01:05:56,240 --> 01:05:57,640
And I kept a scrapbook.

980
01:05:57,640 --> 01:06:00,640
I wish I had kept it years.

981
01:06:00,640 --> 01:06:03,760
I remember one day taking it up to my play mama's house.

982
01:06:03,760 --> 01:06:07,160
We had these teenage girls who would be your play mama.

983
01:06:07,160 --> 01:06:10,520
They were like, nice to you and so on.

984
01:06:10,520 --> 01:06:14,560
Like a young sister and man was Modell Stewart.

985
01:06:14,560 --> 01:06:20,600
I remember one day taking this scrapbook to her house.

986
01:06:20,600 --> 01:06:26,520
And I remember laying on the floor on that stomach, flipping through it, showing it to her.

987
01:06:26,520 --> 01:06:30,720
I remember crying.

988
01:06:30,720 --> 01:06:36,200
And feeling so terrible, evolvable, both the same time feeling that one day I'm going

989
01:06:36,200 --> 01:06:37,920
to do something about this.

990
01:06:37,920 --> 01:06:43,080
That was always the feeling that you could see these horrible things happening to people.

991
01:06:43,080 --> 01:06:47,400
But one day, it's not going to be like this because I'm going to help to change it.

992
01:06:47,400 --> 01:06:55,440
I'll never forget how the second lynching we experienced was that of McCharles Parker and

993
01:06:55,440 --> 01:06:59,480
Poplarville, which is now 15 minutes from Hattiesburg back then.

994
01:06:59,480 --> 01:07:03,360
It was probably 45 on the old roads.

995
01:07:03,360 --> 01:07:08,760
And that was close to home.

996
01:07:08,760 --> 01:07:13,760
I remember the international media came to Hattiesburg because Hattiesburg had a hotel.

997
01:07:13,760 --> 01:07:17,160
It was the largest city in the hub city.

998
01:07:17,160 --> 01:07:20,720
At least smaller towns nearby.

999
01:07:20,720 --> 01:07:24,640
And during that, we go up to town as we call it.

1000
01:07:24,640 --> 01:07:26,960
Get on the bus and put it down.

1001
01:07:26,960 --> 01:07:32,160
We stood on the streets listening to these international reporters, foreign accents and

1002
01:07:32,160 --> 01:07:33,160
speaking in a foreign town.

1003
01:07:33,160 --> 01:07:35,960
And one time we were just pretending we were foreign too.

1004
01:07:35,960 --> 01:07:37,960
We were just sitting on the roof.

1005
01:07:37,960 --> 01:07:39,960
We were just sitting on the roof.

1006
01:07:39,960 --> 01:07:40,960
That was the roof.

1007
01:07:40,960 --> 01:07:42,440
Like making up words.

1008
01:07:42,440 --> 01:07:46,560
But I felt that they were our friends.

1009
01:07:46,560 --> 01:07:47,560
They were friends.

1010
01:07:47,560 --> 01:07:50,640
Our friends because they're here to tell the world about this.

1011
01:07:50,640 --> 01:07:57,400
And anytime I saw anyone that I felt was exposing what's going on, I felt a sense of empowerment.

1012
01:07:57,400 --> 01:08:02,400
But I remember also after McCharles Parker was lynched.

1013
01:08:02,400 --> 01:08:10,140
And as I said, it was so close to home that I remember my mother was starting pulling

1014
01:08:10,140 --> 01:08:12,840
the boys and my father in close.

1015
01:08:12,840 --> 01:08:15,960
I prayed to you better be brother next to me.

1016
01:08:15,960 --> 01:08:18,440
And I prayed to you home before dark.

1017
01:08:18,440 --> 01:08:25,940
I mean, it was like that natural, that protective instinct was to make sure that, because in

1018
01:08:25,940 --> 01:08:29,880
a way after I mentioned, we felt there was a lot of fallout from it.

1019
01:08:29,880 --> 01:08:31,800
It was not an isolated event.

1020
01:08:31,800 --> 01:08:34,920
It empowered the racist because they would stand out.

1021
01:08:34,920 --> 01:08:37,880
That chest stuck out and they'd talk about the niggers.

1022
01:08:37,880 --> 01:08:39,840
This is the niggers that they should have killed.

1023
01:08:39,840 --> 01:08:40,840
I wish I'd been there.

1024
01:08:40,840 --> 01:08:43,520
I would have done whatever to them.

1025
01:08:43,520 --> 01:08:48,160
I would have kicked them to a, I would have gotten me a shot on them.

1026
01:08:48,160 --> 01:08:57,280
And so these were catalytic agents for all the racism just to flourish out in the open.

1027
01:08:57,280 --> 01:09:04,000
And so it was that which you feared as much as the actual event that had occurred as well.

1028
01:09:04,000 --> 01:09:06,600
Because it was like the climate coming forth.

1029
01:09:07,160 --> 01:09:10,840
It's like Sarah Palin getting out here stirring up the tea party.

1030
01:09:10,840 --> 01:09:16,720
It's not just Palin, Michelle Bachman, but when they come around and they start talking

1031
01:09:16,720 --> 01:09:21,000
then all the other people who feel like them come out as well.

1032
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:23,440
And that was the way I felt with these lynchings.

1033
01:09:23,440 --> 01:09:29,120
But the other side of it is the same perpetrators lived in the community and lived next door

1034
01:09:29,120 --> 01:09:33,040
exactly and everybody knew who they were.

1035
01:09:33,120 --> 01:09:37,000
But just the man who killed Mr. Vernon Damer.

1036
01:09:37,000 --> 01:09:42,480
He lived in the black community, had a little store, whatever in the community.

1037
01:09:42,480 --> 01:09:46,080
Everybody knew who he was and you couldn't do anything about it.

1038
01:09:46,080 --> 01:09:50,560
And one of the most, while I'm thinking about it, one of the most horrendous times that

1039
01:09:50,560 --> 01:09:58,160
I experienced was when we went to found Kofo in August of 1962 in Clarksdale, Mississippi.

1040
01:09:58,160 --> 01:10:04,280
This was my first time going to the Delta after Emmett Teales and all this had happened.

1041
01:10:04,280 --> 01:10:10,040
Bob Moses, Dave Dennis, Maddie Dennis, Koeladel.

1042
01:10:10,040 --> 01:10:14,120
I'm not sure quite a few of us went up there.

1043
01:10:14,120 --> 01:10:16,160
And Clarksdale had a curfew.

1044
01:10:16,160 --> 01:10:17,160
I didn't know that.

1045
01:10:17,160 --> 01:10:20,120
All blacks off the street at 12 midnight.

1046
01:10:20,120 --> 01:10:24,760
And when we got into the church, sure enough we got into the church, here comes a fire truck.

1047
01:10:24,760 --> 01:10:26,560
There's no fire here.

1048
01:10:26,560 --> 01:10:35,120
And so when the meeting was over, we were all subject to being arrested for passing the curfew.

1049
01:10:35,120 --> 01:10:36,440
And then we didn't know anything about it.

1050
01:10:36,440 --> 01:10:42,840
On our way trying to get to Jackson and it was dark in a thousand midnight in the Delta.

1051
01:10:42,840 --> 01:10:46,200
You've been up there, you don't see anything but the stars.

1052
01:10:46,200 --> 01:10:51,820
And so Dave Dennis was driving our car and we, the police got us before we got the Mount

1053
01:10:51,820 --> 01:10:54,140
Bayer, which is the old black town.

1054
01:10:54,140 --> 01:11:00,620
And so we stopped along this dark road and the police took him to his car and talked

1055
01:11:00,620 --> 01:11:01,620
about him.

1056
01:11:01,620 --> 01:11:04,380
Dave is a mixed heritage.

1057
01:11:04,380 --> 01:11:06,140
He discussed that with him.

1058
01:11:06,140 --> 01:11:08,620
Then he told me he was going to take him to jail.

1059
01:11:08,620 --> 01:11:15,260
And so Dave came and told us to follow him back to Clarksdale to the jail because he was

1060
01:11:15,260 --> 01:11:16,540
going to lock him up.

1061
01:11:16,540 --> 01:11:22,260
So we didn't know anything about the Delta and Lester McKinney, who was one of the freedom

1062
01:11:22,260 --> 01:11:25,780
riders from Nashville, was driving the car.

1063
01:11:25,780 --> 01:11:32,500
And so when we got to Clarksdale to the jail, the officer went and said, get the F out

1064
01:11:32,500 --> 01:11:34,300
of Clarksdale.

1065
01:11:34,300 --> 01:11:38,620
And so here we are riding around and around and around and around trying to find Amzen

1066
01:11:38,620 --> 01:11:39,620
Moore's house.

1067
01:11:39,620 --> 01:11:45,540
Amzen Moore was a World War I veteran who had worked on a lot of work in Mississippi with

1068
01:11:45,540 --> 01:11:48,140
the NWCP and 102.

1069
01:11:48,140 --> 01:11:50,140
And what was it?

1070
01:11:50,140 --> 01:11:55,100
It may have been two, but it would have been maybe two.

1071
01:11:55,100 --> 01:12:03,260
But anyway, he was known had a reputation for trying to work in the community and very

1072
01:12:03,260 --> 01:12:06,140
courageous man who got out of his way.

1073
01:12:06,140 --> 01:12:10,540
He hosted Bob Moses and so forth when Bob came down.

1074
01:12:10,540 --> 01:12:14,060
And so we were trying to find his house in Cleveland.

1075
01:12:14,060 --> 01:12:18,860
And we rode around and around and it was daylight, like six o'clock.

1076
01:12:18,860 --> 01:12:22,860
We had to go through Rueville and we had been told at Mowlum, one of the men who killed

1077
01:12:22,860 --> 01:12:26,460
Emmett Till was the night washman in Rueville.

1078
01:12:26,460 --> 01:12:32,300
And blacks were to be off the streets there at 10 o'clock at night.

1079
01:12:32,300 --> 01:12:37,460
And so when we got to Rueville, I said, Lester, don't go 20 and don't go under 20.

1080
01:12:37,460 --> 01:12:41,380
It was like you were paralyzed with fear.

1081
01:12:41,380 --> 01:12:46,380
And those are the conditions that people were living under and made it some still or I

1082
01:12:46,380 --> 01:12:47,380
don't know.

1083
01:12:47,380 --> 01:12:52,180
And then we said, we're going to do something about this right there in the Delta.

1084
01:12:52,180 --> 01:12:56,980
And that's how we decided that we were going to go and working the Delta, go and work with

1085
01:12:56,980 --> 01:13:00,700
the share crops and bring people like Miss Hamon to the courthouse to register.

1086
01:13:00,700 --> 01:13:02,780
That was where we stopped right there.

1087
01:13:02,780 --> 01:13:03,780
Exactly.

1088
01:13:03,780 --> 01:13:05,780
Let me go ahead and wait for a moment.

1089
01:13:05,780 --> 01:13:12,780
Did you do a lot of genealogy, research, delivery, Congress, or what were you looking for?

1090
01:13:12,780 --> 01:13:13,780
I have a few thoughts.

1091
01:13:13,780 --> 01:13:14,780
Okay.

1092
01:13:14,780 --> 01:13:15,780
On my questions and we will come to that.

1093
01:13:15,780 --> 01:13:16,780
Of course, yes.

1094
01:13:16,780 --> 01:13:19,780
It's obviously a very important issue.

1095
01:13:19,780 --> 01:13:20,780
Thank you.

1096
01:13:20,780 --> 01:13:24,780
That's a very, and I want to ask just one quick question on the way.

1097
01:13:24,780 --> 01:13:30,780
I'm thinking back of the work, how you were drawn in youth council and Emmett,

1098
01:13:30,780 --> 01:13:34,780
did you ever meet a no-root bond rocks bro?

1099
01:13:34,780 --> 01:13:35,780
I've never heard of it.

1100
01:13:35,780 --> 01:13:39,780
National, official and so she was also a serious contributor.

1101
01:13:39,780 --> 01:13:40,780
I just wondered if you knew in that context.

1102
01:13:40,780 --> 01:13:44,780
We met Ruben Hurley, who was the southeastern director of the NWCT.

1103
01:13:44,780 --> 01:13:45,780
Sure.

1104
01:13:45,780 --> 01:13:47,780
Let me have you.

1105
01:13:47,780 --> 01:13:51,780
I'm very interested in each of you have talked a little bit about your first experience

1106
01:13:51,780 --> 01:13:59,780
is going in to do local organizing, to the breaking that you mentioned in the Delta and

1107
01:13:59,780 --> 01:14:01,780
that context, really, 62.

1108
01:14:01,780 --> 01:14:10,780
The difference between us was that I always had one foot in the University of college and

1109
01:14:10,780 --> 01:14:14,780
one out and Dury dropped out of school.

1110
01:14:14,780 --> 01:14:19,780
Dury told me once, Joyce, I can't stay in school and no matter how people are suffering.

1111
01:14:19,780 --> 01:14:23,780
And I was always trying to figure out how I could do both.

1112
01:14:23,780 --> 01:14:28,780
So, when she left college, I was very upset, but at the same time I knew that

1113
01:14:29,780 --> 01:14:30,780
was her calling.

1114
01:14:30,780 --> 01:14:35,780
And I always did my movement work alongside my campus work.

1115
01:14:35,780 --> 01:14:40,780
I was more campus-based in a way.

1116
01:14:40,780 --> 01:14:46,780
But still spent time, you know, I didn't communicate organizing as well.

1117
01:14:46,780 --> 01:14:51,780
Well, the experience that I just described to you about going into Delta 1962,

1118
01:14:51,780 --> 01:14:56,780
this was also the time that James Meredith was enrolling in Ole Miss.

1119
01:14:57,780 --> 01:15:03,780
So, it was particularly horrendous time for the state of Mississippi.

1120
01:15:03,780 --> 01:15:06,780
And I made a decision.

1121
01:15:06,780 --> 01:15:08,780
I had left home that summer.

1122
01:15:08,780 --> 01:15:13,780
Joyce went to Chicago and to California with my uncle, Fontaine.

1123
01:15:13,780 --> 01:15:20,780
And I decided to go and work with Bob Moses in Jackson for my freedom as I told my mother

1124
01:15:20,780 --> 01:15:23,780
on my way out the door with my own surprise.

1125
01:15:23,780 --> 01:15:24,780
She said.

1126
01:15:25,780 --> 01:15:29,780
Wait a minute, let me tell my own story, please.

1127
01:15:29,780 --> 01:15:34,780
I said, Mother, well, shouldn't I?

1128
01:15:34,780 --> 01:15:39,780
I said, Mother, I packed a few little pieces and had a little small orange suitcase.

1129
01:15:39,780 --> 01:15:45,780
I said, Mother, I'm going to go to Jackson and work with Bob Moses to get my freedom

1130
01:15:45,780 --> 01:15:50,780
as I was going out the door to go downtown to catch the greyhound bus.

1131
01:15:50,780 --> 01:15:53,780
And Mother turned around to look.

1132
01:15:53,780 --> 01:15:57,780
But Mother had other children there.

1133
01:15:57,780 --> 01:16:07,780
And so, I went on downtown, got on the bus and went to Jackson and to the Freedom House on Rose Street.

1134
01:16:07,780 --> 01:16:10,780
And Mother turned to me and said, What's she saying?

1135
01:16:10,780 --> 01:16:11,780
She's going where?

1136
01:16:11,780 --> 01:16:15,780
And so, I was left to explain where she was going.

1137
01:16:15,780 --> 01:16:17,780
And you went to California that summer.

1138
01:16:17,780 --> 01:16:19,780
Well, I went to Chicago to work.

1139
01:16:19,780 --> 01:16:22,780
Then I went with them to California.

1140
01:16:22,780 --> 01:16:31,780
And so, that particular summer was the first summer that I had really dedicated my whole life

1141
01:16:31,780 --> 01:16:34,780
has been dedicated to the cause.

1142
01:16:34,780 --> 01:16:42,780
And from what I experienced that particular night on the roadside, there in the Delta,

1143
01:16:42,780 --> 01:16:51,780
and curfews which I had never heard of made me more determined to do something about the social change in that state

1144
01:16:51,780 --> 01:16:55,780
and throughout the United States of America.

1145
01:16:55,780 --> 01:17:01,780
And the other thing was that this energy that the Freedom Riders brought to the state of Mississippi.

1146
01:17:01,780 --> 01:17:03,780
So, these were young people.

1147
01:17:03,780 --> 01:17:10,780
We had been at Jackson State and James Meredith was one of our strategists at Jackson State.

1148
01:17:10,780 --> 01:17:19,780
And we had gone to demonstrate in behalf of the Tugulu 9 and tear gas.

1149
01:17:19,780 --> 01:17:27,780
But James Meredith was a great strategist, very clear-headed and level-headed.

1150
01:17:27,780 --> 01:17:30,780
But we had no idea he was going to Ole Miss, you know, he never meant to.

1151
01:17:30,780 --> 01:17:38,780
But then we were a torch it socially and otherwise at Jackson State.

1152
01:17:38,780 --> 01:17:41,780
We got expelled too.

1153
01:17:41,780 --> 01:17:46,780
And see, Meg Evans' office was across the street and every Wednesday we would go in and talk to him about our freedom,

1154
01:17:46,780 --> 01:17:47,780
which was abstract.

1155
01:17:47,780 --> 01:17:49,780
All we want to know was about our freedom.

1156
01:17:49,780 --> 01:17:51,780
We're going to get our freedom one day.

1157
01:17:51,780 --> 01:17:58,780
And we just had to ask him about what's going on with the movement, about Negro rights around Mississippi.

1158
01:17:58,780 --> 01:18:02,780
Because we'd ask him and he said, well, I went up to the Delta.

1159
01:18:02,780 --> 01:18:07,780
Or I went, one day he came on the campus and brought me some money because he had been in Hattestburg.

1160
01:18:07,780 --> 01:18:11,780
He was in a grocery store and he saw Met Moth.

1161
01:18:11,780 --> 01:18:20,780
I don't know how they got to know who each other was, but she gave him some money and he brought it on campus to kill me.

1162
01:18:20,780 --> 01:18:23,780
And we wanted to be a part of the Tugulu 9.

1163
01:18:23,780 --> 01:18:28,780
We asked him if we could join, he told us there was going to be a demonstration.

1164
01:18:28,780 --> 01:18:29,780
Can we join? Can we join?

1165
01:18:29,780 --> 01:18:31,780
First, he said, yeah, yeah, that would be good.

1166
01:18:31,780 --> 01:18:36,780
And then he said, on the other hand, no, because he started thinking about it.

1167
01:18:36,780 --> 01:18:42,780
He said, you would be expelled immediately because you can't sign out to go to the public library.

1168
01:18:42,780 --> 01:18:48,780
And he said, well, why don't you do something on the campus?

1169
01:18:48,780 --> 01:18:50,780
And Dury was president of the dorm council.

1170
01:18:50,780 --> 01:18:55,780
And she, well, always prayed before everything, events occurred.

1171
01:18:55,780 --> 01:18:59,780
