01:37:23,780 --> 01:37:27,780
So cars, we traveled in a fleet together.

1389
01:37:27,780 --> 01:37:30,780
So I think it was about three cars together.

1390
01:37:30,780 --> 01:37:33,780
I'll never forget that trip up there.

1391
01:37:33,780 --> 01:37:38,780
And then once we got there, I stayed at the Y.

1392
01:37:38,780 --> 01:37:41,780
I stayed in a little small hotel.

1393
01:37:41,780 --> 01:37:46,780
Yeah, that was the convention, the FNPs Hotel.

1394
01:37:46,780 --> 01:37:50,780
And we had the Burnout Station wagon on the boardwalk.

1395
01:37:50,780 --> 01:37:51,780
Right.

1396
01:37:51,780 --> 01:37:52,780
For the front.

1397
01:37:52,780 --> 01:37:55,780
The swarrow chain and good men.

1398
01:37:55,780 --> 01:38:12,780
It was a car that Mickey, Michael Swarrow, James Cheney and Andrew Goodman were driving when they were killed by a recent kill by the sheriff in deputy and local people in Phyllida,

1399
01:38:12,780 --> 01:38:14,780
and they burned it up after the car afterwards.

1400
01:38:14,780 --> 01:38:22,780
And the Chokto native found it in the swamps, in the woods there in the showroom county.

1401
01:38:22,780 --> 01:38:34,780
And we told that car up to Atlantic City, put it on the boardwalk, and different people stood there and explained what it was as people at the convention stopped.

1402
01:38:34,780 --> 01:38:38,780
And I remember being standing there and people wanted to know, what is that?

1403
01:38:38,780 --> 01:38:41,780
And then once you told them, this is what the three freedom routers,

1404
01:38:41,780 --> 01:38:55,780
three civil rights workers were in, driving when they were killed, then it just took on, I mean, it was this symbolic manifestation of just the most other type of fear and they could understand.

1405
01:38:55,780 --> 01:39:04,780
See, one thing we understood in the movement, and I'm not sure how, as young as we were, how we understood, came to understand it, but we showed people what it was like as much as possible.

1406
01:39:04,780 --> 01:39:27,780
It was a tactile thing, like lots of photographs, a lot of booklets we put together, freedom ballots, literacy books, teaching plantation workers, literacy, you might have a sentence that one sack of cotton weighs 80 pounds, another way is whatever.

1407
01:39:27,780 --> 01:39:33,780
And total is 160 pounds, but we used things from the environment.

1408
01:39:33,780 --> 01:39:42,780
And so taking that car to the boardwalk in Atlantic City, for everyone to see that this is what the three civil rights workers were driving.

1409
01:39:42,780 --> 01:39:55,780
And then you know you've heard that they were murdered, bodies were found, and they burned this car like this, and people were just, wow, we could understand why this Mississippi segregated delegation shouldn't be seated.

1410
01:39:56,780 --> 01:40:14,780
And I had seen them at Miami University in Oxfowl, Ohio, as they were leaving to return to Mississippi because they had, we'd gotten this call that the church had burned and making up a course with, and James were, what, immediately returned.

1411
01:40:14,780 --> 01:40:27,780
And, and they jumped in the car, he was a volunteer, he had not been to Mississippi before, so we went out to the car and told them together.

1412
01:40:27,780 --> 01:40:42,780
And word came back that they had not been heard from through the Watt's land, and I remember in the meeting volunteers were running around, you know, full of energy.

1413
01:40:42,780 --> 01:40:47,780
And then we said, this is very serious, very serious.

1414
01:40:47,780 --> 01:40:55,780
And Herbert Randall captured a picture of me, he may have seen it with my arm out wearing a white blouse.

1415
01:40:55,780 --> 01:41:06,780
And he explained me what happened was that I was talking and explained the seriousness of what was going on that we knew they were dead.

1416
01:41:06,780 --> 01:41:20,780
And then I took it outside and continued to talk. And then he captured a picture of me sitting there with my head about, we all knew they were dead because you had so many hours or minutes to check in.

1417
01:41:20,780 --> 01:41:25,780
Right. Once you didn't check in, then we started calling.

1418
01:41:25,780 --> 01:41:40,780
But we blame the federal government for not intervening earlier, and they could have been saved because I heard recently that some of the cooks who worked at the jail had told people in the community that they had the word out there in the jail.

1419
01:41:40,780 --> 01:41:49,780
And they didn't. And that was something that we had to live with and really, really, really disturbed us.

1420
01:41:49,780 --> 01:41:58,780
So what I often have thought about over the years is we were so young to have been exposed to so much death and so much violence.

1421
01:41:58,780 --> 01:42:08,780
And some people, what we call our walking wounded, they didn't survive it intact. I mean, the movement destroyed them.

1422
01:42:08,780 --> 01:42:15,780
I won't say the movement destroyed them, but they were the casualties of the movement. And we don't talk about them enough.

1423
01:42:15,780 --> 01:42:23,780
But to be 18, 19, 20, if you were 25 and snick you were older, considered old.

1424
01:42:23,780 --> 01:42:33,780
But to be 18, 19, 20 years old and you're exposed to all this danger and all of this violence and all of this fear all the time.

1425
01:42:33,780 --> 01:42:38,780
It's a wonder that as many people survived as did. It's truly remarkable, I think.

1426
01:42:38,780 --> 01:42:45,780
When they came to Berk, attempted to blow our house up, our office up in the natures.

1427
01:42:45,780 --> 01:42:50,780
They blew up the wrong house according to the fire chief. I asked him who's house was that, who's ours.

1428
01:42:50,780 --> 01:43:00,780
And they had burned bomb through a cocktail and this cafe that belonged to an integrated couple according to the police chief. He had known them since he was a kid.

1429
01:43:00,780 --> 01:43:12,780
And he was a Jake Fishman and his black mistress. And so we, there were mob of people there.

1430
01:43:12,780 --> 01:43:19,780
We got word that our office had been blown up. So we ran over there. Every white person in the natures knew it was going to be blown up.

1431
01:43:19,780 --> 01:43:34,780
And we got there. They were standing all around like in an alley and we had to go through there and Mr. Archie Curtis, the funeral director, was there with his attendant.

1432
01:43:34,780 --> 01:43:44,780
So we felt that we had to go inside and get the names of the people who had signed up with us on the full by four cards.

1433
01:43:44,780 --> 01:43:51,780
And prior to that, John Doah had been sending two justice department officials down there.

1434
01:43:51,780 --> 01:43:58,780
Young white guys were sawing our shot. They let us see them. They said they weren't coming anymore because it was getting too dangerous.

1435
01:43:58,780 --> 01:44:07,780
We were coming to check on us every week to see if we were alive. And so they weren't coming back. And this is when the attempt was to blow up the office, but to make it long story short.

1436
01:44:07,780 --> 01:44:17,780
We went, Mr. Curtis said, I'll take you all in there to get those names and nobody's going to bother you. And so we went inside. We had turned the light on and come out.

1437
01:44:17,780 --> 01:44:24,780
We went through the model people and got in the car and drove back to Mr. George Medcalfe's boarding house.

1438
01:44:24,780 --> 01:44:30,780
And the phone rang all night until I told this woman, who kept calling, door you, MF, just that.

1439
01:44:30,780 --> 01:44:37,780
I said, you know what? Little Richie is coming to the town. I said, you like little Richie? Yes, I like little Richie.

1440
01:44:37,780 --> 01:44:43,780
I said, well, if you don't call anymore, I'll get you a ticket. You will, Dory. I said, yes. I promise you I'll get you a ticket.

1441
01:44:43,780 --> 01:44:46,780
I said, you don't need to worry. Thank you so much.

1442
01:44:46,780 --> 01:44:49,780
There was a lot of danger. I remember.

1443
01:44:49,780 --> 01:44:52,780
It's sanity. It's sanity. Right. It gets a frenzy.

1444
01:44:52,780 --> 01:45:00,780
I mean, it's psyche. The cash, WJ cash, wrote about in mind of the South, is so appropriate here.

1445
01:45:00,780 --> 01:45:08,780
I remember being in Greenwood in spring of 64.

1446
01:45:08,780 --> 01:45:18,780
It was in 63. 63. And the police, not the police, but I worked in the SNCC office all day that day.

1447
01:45:18,780 --> 01:45:24,780
And I was one who didn't mind doing office work.

1448
01:45:24,780 --> 01:45:30,780
And then that night, left office, almost midnight.

1449
01:45:30,780 --> 01:45:34,780
Went home, learned they'd blown up the office that night.

1450
01:45:34,780 --> 01:45:40,780
And the morning got up and found out about it, went in there and cleaned up all the files, got retrieved everything possible.

1451
01:45:40,780 --> 01:45:45,780
And I don't think, I mean, a satire in the momentary danger, but you say, oh, that's horrible.

1452
01:45:45,780 --> 01:45:51,780
But we did skip a beat. You know, the next day, we were out there again trying to get people to go down to the,

1453
01:45:51,780 --> 01:45:57,780
but going with people down to Greenwood, the Florida County Courthouse to register vote.

1454
01:45:57,780 --> 01:46:03,780
And these police dogs that chasing us and here come, along come someone, hollering.

1455
01:46:03,780 --> 01:46:10,780
Where is the pay phone? Where is the pay phone? And I said, I said, she's, I want to call the Justice Department.

1456
01:46:10,780 --> 01:46:13,780
And I stopped at Justice Department. I want to call the Justice Department.

1457
01:46:13,780 --> 01:46:17,780
I didn't know any black person who knew anyone in the Justice Department to call.

1458
01:46:17,780 --> 01:46:22,780
So I was taking a back. I found that more curious than the dogs chasing us.

1459
01:46:22,780 --> 01:46:29,780
So I turned around and turned out to be Marion Wright, who was at Yale Law School.

1460
01:46:29,780 --> 01:46:39,780
And she had spent some of her interning at the Justice Department, but she was there that spring break working with us at Greenwood Voter Registration Campaign.

1461
01:46:39,780 --> 01:46:46,780
And I told her about that years later and she said, and you know what, I was calling John Doerr and she said, you know what he told me?

1462
01:46:46,780 --> 01:46:49,780
I said, what, she said, calm down, calm down, tell me what happened.

1463
01:46:49,780 --> 01:46:53,780
I said, and then Mr. The Dogs chasing us, that was easy for him to say.

1464
01:46:53,780 --> 01:47:01,780
And one thing that I left out about the bond was that there was a local young lady from the National Black With Us.

1465
01:47:01,780 --> 01:47:07,780
She had a daceted tooth faint of fall out on the ground.

1466
01:47:07,780 --> 01:47:12,780
And what was I going to do with this? If you choose to faint here, I'm stepping over you.

1467
01:47:12,780 --> 01:47:16,780
We go in in the office and I'll leave you here. I don't know what happened to her.

1468
01:47:16,780 --> 01:47:22,780
But that was the, the man said, you don't, you didn't have time to do certain things.

1469
01:47:22,780 --> 01:47:29,780
No, and you didn't faint. But I had the amazing capacity that I didn't know I had. I've analyzed it many years later.

1470
01:47:29,780 --> 01:47:36,780
To be in the dangerous situations and separate myself from it almost, it was like almost being out of body.

1471
01:47:36,780 --> 01:47:42,780
Like the next morning I got up and went, cleaned up the files and didn't even really deal with what had just happened emotionally.

1472
01:47:42,780 --> 01:47:44,780
I just didn't deal with it.

1473
01:47:44,780 --> 01:47:47,780
So, relative we close to the end of the day.

1474
01:47:47,780 --> 01:47:49,780
Okay, sure. Why don't you ask what you said.

1475
01:47:49,780 --> 01:47:56,780
Let me just, I definitely want to ask a few things to make sure that we can actually hear your sense of a few things.

1476
01:47:56,780 --> 01:48:01,780
I must be close out here and I'll have time for any final comments for you as well.

1477
01:48:01,780 --> 01:48:12,780
But let me mention the, the, the, the, the, the, the terms used in kind of a form of a way to talk about the people who suffered from, from witnessing all this violence, the law being wounded.

1478
01:48:12,780 --> 01:48:22,780
Right. And I wonder if there are any things that more that you would like, I don't really like to talk about the legacy of that violence being so close to that much violence.

1479
01:48:22,780 --> 01:48:26,780
But personally, enduring it and witnessing it at close hand.

1480
01:48:26,780 --> 01:48:36,780
Well, and now this day that the term terrorism is used, it doesn't phase me because I've lived through all that.

1481
01:48:36,780 --> 01:48:39,780
I've lived through, I've seen that was terrible.

1482
01:48:39,780 --> 01:48:40,780
That was terrible.

1483
01:48:40,780 --> 01:48:47,780
And to churches, and to homes, more than I can count right now.

1484
01:48:47,780 --> 01:48:52,780
And being chased, I never, I didn't know how to drive at the time.

1485
01:48:52,780 --> 01:49:04,780
And I would always sit in the back seat of a car because for fear that whoever was driving, and another driver sitting in front seat, for fear that if a guy would come by and pick up truck with a rebel flag and a gun.

1486
01:49:04,780 --> 01:49:15,780
That the next person would take over wheel that Jimmy Travis was shot in the Mississippi in 1963.

1487
01:49:15,780 --> 01:49:23,780
So there are some things now that flash across my mind like PTSD at times.

1488
01:49:24,780 --> 01:49:30,780
And you don't realize until it surfaces.

1489
01:49:30,780 --> 01:49:45,780
But the violence part, when I didn't happen to, it doesn't affect me in the same way because I personally lived through it.

1490
01:49:45,780 --> 01:49:48,780
So I don't get all upset.

1491
01:49:48,780 --> 01:49:51,780
You've been so sensitized to this.

1492
01:49:51,780 --> 01:49:54,780
It's something that happened.

1493
01:49:54,780 --> 01:50:03,780
And I'm not condoning it, but it's something that you just sort of, sort of, is in your whole psyche.

1494
01:50:03,780 --> 01:50:06,780
I don't think I've dealt with a lot of things that happened.

1495
01:50:06,780 --> 01:50:08,780
I think I just sublimated a lot of stuff.

1496
01:50:08,780 --> 01:50:12,780
And I believe a lot of it went into my work.

1497
01:50:13,780 --> 01:50:20,780
I believe that I worked very, very hard because I loved working.

1498
01:50:20,780 --> 01:50:27,780
And I pushed myself, I was driven, just very driven in my work.

1499
01:50:27,780 --> 01:50:40,780
And I think that a lot of it came from not only being a very active, engaging mind that caused me to want to seek more knowledge and write books and do research and so on.

1500
01:50:40,780 --> 01:50:43,780
I did the administrative teacher and all those things.

1501
01:50:43,780 --> 01:50:49,780
But I think also it was to keep me, I didn't have to remember a lot of things either.

1502
01:50:49,780 --> 01:50:57,780
And I spent several years working in Level 1 Trauma Unit.

1503
01:50:57,780 --> 01:51:10,780
For me, it was like out of my experience, although working with certain death and all this kind of stuff, I was like prepared to work with it.

1504
01:51:10,780 --> 01:51:17,780
And although I said I never want to say that I've got used to the sight of blood, that means I'm no longer human.

1505
01:51:17,780 --> 01:51:24,780
But I was sort of desensitized to a lot of stuff that I saw tragedy.

1506
01:51:24,780 --> 01:51:33,780
I'll tell you that in spite of all that, my very worst moment in the entire movement came on the early that morning 6 a.m.

1507
01:51:33,780 --> 01:51:38,780
So morning, my mother called to say Mr. Dame was killed.

1508
01:51:38,780 --> 01:51:40,780
It was 6 to 6.

1509
01:51:40,780 --> 01:51:43,780
I'll never forget that I was in graduate school in my apartment.

1510
01:51:43,780 --> 01:51:48,780
And I just stood there and broke down and just started screaming and crying.

1511
01:51:48,780 --> 01:51:59,780
All those years of repressing so much, and what I couldn't understand, because I was always, I never reacted entirely emotional to things.

1512
01:51:59,780 --> 01:52:16,780
I was usually filtered through my mind first and I was like, I can't understand then, how he lived through the worst, the most fearful, terrible, time of the movement and then to die after all of the violence,

1513
01:52:16,780 --> 01:52:25,780
after the most violent period that I couldn't reconcile.

1514
01:52:25,780 --> 01:52:35,780
One more thing about Lennox City, we were assigned to work with, to lobby with different members of Freedom Democratic Party delegation.

1515
01:52:35,780 --> 01:52:39,780
And I was assigned with Mr. Mrs. Hartman Turnbull.

1516
01:52:39,780 --> 01:52:43,780
Mr. Turnbull, we always called his wife Mrs. Sweet's.

1517
01:52:43,780 --> 01:52:51,780
And we were to lobby the Oregon delegation with Edith Green, Congresswoman, Edith Green, and Senator Wayne Morris.

1518
01:52:51,780 --> 01:53:00,780
Now, I'll never forget going into the hotel, into the sweet, not a beautiful suite in this hotel, like a penthouse.

1519
01:53:00,780 --> 01:53:04,780
Edith Green was wearing a beautiful caftain.

1520
01:53:04,780 --> 01:53:13,780
And Mr. Turnbull presented the case of the FTP very clearly, and then Mrs. Turnbull was very quiet, she never said anything.

1521
01:53:13,780 --> 01:53:17,780
She was carrying a brown paper bag, she had a pistol in it.

1522
01:53:17,780 --> 01:53:22,780
I always thought that was just so fantastic. I thought that was a gas man.

1523
01:53:22,780 --> 01:53:25,780
I loved it. I loved it.

1524
01:53:25,780 --> 01:53:32,780
You know, their home had been blown up, and then he was accused of being the bum of his own home.

1525
01:53:32,780 --> 01:53:35,780
So she didn't trust these people in Lennox City.

1526
01:53:35,780 --> 01:53:40,780
She had a gun. I thought it was a, you know, when you're young, you just see the iron in all kinds of stuff.

1527
01:53:40,780 --> 01:53:42,780
I thought that was great.

1528
01:53:42,780 --> 01:53:44,780
Most people had guns.

1529
01:53:44,780 --> 01:53:47,780
A lot of people had guns, and they didn't say anything about it.

1530
01:53:47,780 --> 01:54:02,780
You just mentioned iron in it that there are, I don't know, that's iron in the white, but there are so many layers of complication to sort out an emulation of the question of your experience that came out of the geneological work,

1531
01:54:02,780 --> 01:54:08,780
which is that of course there's this whole contemporary white side of the family, so to speak.

1532
01:54:08,780 --> 01:54:12,780
Yeah, very interested in your, if you'd like to.

1533
01:54:12,780 --> 01:54:23,780
Well, it came from living in my mother's family, especially. I didn't live around my father's side because they all had a Mocha Chicago in California.

1534
01:54:23,780 --> 01:54:33,780
And my mother and her brothers were always different, meaning that they were malatos, Indians, or whatever.

1535
01:54:33,780 --> 01:54:41,780
And they would talk about their life and being wooled was a...

1536
01:54:41,780 --> 01:54:50,780
The Dippity was a man who called the Copeland Gang, and so they called them a squatter, yes.

1537
01:54:50,780 --> 01:54:54,780
Spotter, spot like you spot these crops.

1538
01:54:54,780 --> 01:55:09,780
So I was intrigued, and also was intrigued by my mother's family because they were different from most people in the community, the hair and coloration and so forth.

1539
01:55:09,780 --> 01:55:12,780
They looked Indian.

1540
01:55:12,780 --> 01:55:24,780
And after listening to Canadian broadcasts and one night in 1992, they were making them move in Jackson Freedom Song.

1541
01:55:24,780 --> 01:55:34,780
So they announced on the radio that the Canadian broadcasts and that the archives were open in Jackson, the Civil for Black People, 1992.

1542
01:55:34,780 --> 01:55:38,780
They had finished all the slave records and you could go in and use them.

1543
01:55:38,780 --> 01:55:45,780
So I took the opportunity to go and start doing the research. All of my mother's siblings were alive at the time.

1544
01:55:45,780 --> 01:55:50,780
They lived the 80s and 90s old. And I started collecting information.

1545
01:55:50,780 --> 01:55:55,780
And the more I got into it, it became like a disease, which is still there.

1546
01:55:55,780 --> 01:56:04,780
So to make a long story short, you know, when you're doing research, people are also doing research, the same kind of research.

1547
01:56:04,780 --> 01:56:12,780
And someone saw that I was researching the same great, great grandfather that this family was.

1548
01:56:12,780 --> 01:56:17,780
And so they were approached and said that you may want to know this or you may not want to know it.

1549
01:56:17,780 --> 01:56:21,780
One in Georgia was approached by a lady in Alabama who was doing her research.

1550
01:56:21,780 --> 01:56:24,780
She said, I want to know it and I have a assistant in England.

1551
01:56:24,780 --> 01:56:33,780
So of course we want to know. So I received a letter from England from London, England saying that we may have a great, great grandfather.

1552
01:56:33,780 --> 01:56:38,780
And I would like to communicate with you and send photographs, exchange photographs.

1553
01:56:38,780 --> 01:56:44,780
And that's how it happened. And we met in Mobile, Alabama.

1554
01:56:44,780 --> 01:56:54,780
And we met again in 1998. And we had two reunions. And we went to the family cemetery.

1555
01:56:54,780 --> 01:56:58,780
And my mother had grown up in Bowies, Mississippi Wayne County.

1556
01:56:58,780 --> 01:57:05,780
And to look at cemetery and also to eat.

1557
01:57:05,780 --> 01:57:17,780
And I spent a great deal of time going into cemeteries looking for a Benjamin F. Willard who was born in 1805 and rocking him North Carolina.

1558
01:57:17,780 --> 01:57:23,780
And we didn't find what we found Benjamin Willard, Jr. who was in the Confederate war.

1559
01:57:23,780 --> 01:57:34,780
And from the information that both sides get collected was that Benjamin Willard had around 11 children, no, 13.

1560
01:57:34,780 --> 01:57:43,780
And five, five, five, five, our great-great-grandmother, Mary, who was described as a black creek Indian.

1561
01:57:43,780 --> 01:57:50,780
But she probably lived in Seminole, come from that part. And they had both, they're both born in 1805.

1562
01:57:50,780 --> 01:57:59,780
And they both came from North Carolina to the Alabama, Mississippi territory together. And they lived together.

1563
01:57:59,780 --> 01:58:14,780
And the first child, Frank, were born 1825. And our great-grandfather was born, Jerry Willard was born in 1870, around 1869, 1870.

1564
01:58:14,780 --> 01:58:24,780
And he was a father of my grandfather, Joseph Collins Willard. And Joseph Collins will marry Martha Gates.

1565
01:58:24,780 --> 01:58:33,780
And our great-grandmother, and she, they'd be 11 children, and my mother was the fifth of 11. And her roots.

1566
01:58:33,780 --> 01:58:42,780
And mother died, mother born May 14, 1921, and she died on January 23, 1995.

1567
01:58:42,780 --> 01:58:45,780
Now my father's side is so-

1568
01:58:45,780 --> 01:58:48,780
He's got something. Stop.

1569
01:58:48,780 --> 01:58:51,780
